The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Rush to join small car race

 OUR CORRESPONDENT

 New Delhi, Sept. 7: The small car segment is revving up for more action.

 While Hyundai Motors (HMIL) today announced its plan to introduce a compact car soon, Japanese companies are busy preparing the route map for the small car race.

 We will come out with a compact car by the end of 2008, said Arvind Saxena, vice-president (marketing and sales), HMIL.

 Though Hyundai refused to share details of the new product, its clear that the Korean carmaker is betting big on the small segment as it has given the company the biggest returns so far. 

 The Santro a compact car launched by Hyundai in 1998 has been a runaway success.

 Honda Siel also plans to introduce its small car in the country to expand its existing product portfolio.

 We are looking at a small car that we will introduce in the Indian market, said Honda Siel CEO M. Takedagawa. He, however, refused to spell out a timeframe for entry.

 To add to the competition, Toyota Hondas arch rival is also planning to come out with a small car. 

 Toyota Kirloskar Motors (TKM), the Japanese carmakers subsidiary in India, says it will introduce a small car in the next two to three years. TKM has been conducting a feasibility study for a long time.

 Toyota Kirloskar MD Atsushi Toyoshima said the companys decision to launch a small car is part of its strategy to corner 10 per cent of the Indian automobile market by 2010. 




